Copy, add, and the build context.

The run instruction builds things. Copy and add bring your own files into the image. But they can only see files inside the build context, so these three ideas really belong together.

Copy takes a source and a destination and copies files or directories from the context. That's all it does. No magic, completely predictable. Add is copy plus two extra behaviours: if the source is a u-r-l, add downloads it; and if the source is a local tarball, add automatically extracts it. Both of those are footguns. The auto-extraction is surprising, and the u-r-l form quietly bypasses your cache discipline. So the best practice is simple: use copy by default, and use run curl instead of add with a u-r-l. Both commands also honour a change-owner flag and a from-stage flag, which we'll use in multi-stage builds later.

Now, the build context. In docker build, dash t, my-image, dot, that final dot is the context. And here's what most people miss: the entire build context is tarballed and sent to the daemon before the build even starts. This matters in two ways. First, if your context is your whole projects folder, with gigabytes of dependencies in it, you'll wait minutes for the upload, even if your docker file copies a single file. So set the context as narrowly as possible; build from the project root, not from your home directory. Second, copy can only see files inside the context. Copying from a path above the context root simply does not work; anything above it is invisible.

That's where the docker-ignore file comes in. It sits at the root of the context and tells the daemon which files to leave out of the tarball. The syntax is like a git-ignore file, one pattern per line. You'd typically exclude the git directory, node modules, Python caches, and any env files. Three payoffs. Faster builds, because the context is smaller. Better cache hits, because a copy-everything layer isn't invalidated by unrelated editor files. And security, because it stops you baking secrets or your git history into a public image. Treat the docker-ignore file as part of every docker file, not as optional.
